04620nam a22006975i 9781400865642DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008656427 a10.1515/97814008656422doi  a(DE-B1597)459898  a(OCoLC)984650505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBUS0970002bisacsh1 aBrockner, Joel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Process Matters :bEngaging and Equipping People for Success /cJoel Brockner.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. It's Only Fair -- t3. Making Change Happen: It's All (or at Least Largely) in the Process -- t4. Taking the Process Personally -- t5. For Ethicality, the Process Also Matters -- t6. A High-Quality Process: Easier Said Than Done -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe do business in a results-oriented world. Our focus on growth is laudable for its clarity, but one of its downsides is that firms can lose sight of the process: how business gets done and the individuals or employees through whom results are achieved. This leads to compromised decisions and unethical behavior. It is not just what we accomplish that matters but also how we accomplish it.In The Process Matters, Joel Brockner shows that managers have to do more than just meet targets and goals. They have to reach those ends in the right ways-with input, consistency, and accountability-if they want to effectively lead and manage in their organizations. Brockner discusses what goes into the right process, how it leads to better outcomes, why it is easier said than done, and how to overcome obstacles along the way.Brockner demonstrates that a high-quality process often costs little and may not even require a great deal of time. In light of these facts, he considers the puzzling question of why good business practice doesn't happen more often. Brockner draws from various real-life workplace examples-from Jay Leno's departure (twice) from his TV show, to the improvement of shooting accuracy in the U.S. Navy, to the surprising results of layoffs in Canada. He also factors in a wide swath of studies to examine such issues as the importance of perceived fairness in the process, the management of organizational change, and the encouragement of a strong sense of self in those involved in decisions-in short, the ways that managers can bring out the best in their people.Relevant to anyone who is in a managerial position-from the CEO on down-The Process Matters proves that seemingly simple differences in process can go a long way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aOrganizational change. 0aReengineering (Management). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Workplace Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400865642zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400865642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400865642.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK